Zur Gefrierschnitt-Autoradiographie am ganzen Tier
items.abstract: <jats:title>Zusammenfassung</jats:title><jats:p>Zur Herstellung von Gefrierschnitten aus ganzen Tieren wurde ein „Ganz-tierschnitt-Kryostat”, zur Erleichterung einzelner Arbeitsgänge ein „Universal-Kryostat” erstellt. Mit Hilfe dieser Geräte wurden verschiedene Methoden zur Schnittgewinnung und Autoradiographie an Ganztierschnitten erprobt.</jats:p><jats:p>Zur unerläßlichen „Versteifung” der Schnitte kann — anstatt „scotch tape” — eine Methacrylat-Äthylacetat-Lösung verwendet werden, mit dem Vorteil besserer Schnittqualität bei verminderter Schnittdicke. Hinsichtlich Auflösung der Ganztierautoradiogramme erwies sich das Mounting-Verfahren erwartungsgemäß als überlegen.</jats:p>

The brachiocephalic artery in the dog with special reference to the arterial supply of the esophagus
items.abstract: <jats:title>Abstract</jats:title><jats:p>Two direct branches of the brachiocephalic artery are frequently present in the dog. These are described in 33 dogs and their incidence recorded. One supplies the lower cervical trachea and esophagus and the other the thymus gland and sometimes the pericardium. Suggested names are “Tracheoesophageal” and “Thymopericardial” branches of the brachiocephalic. The embryology of the blood vessels of the esophagus is discussed and the identification of the tracheoesophageal with a secondary anastomotic vessel is considered most likely. Occasional branches from the brachiocephalic artery in man are reviewed. The Arteria Thyroidea Ima seems to bear the closest relationship to this vessel described in the dog. The value of this study in relation to heart‐lung preparations and to experimental surgery of the esophagus is suggested.</jats:p>

THE ARTERIAL BLOOD SUPPLY TO THE CAT DIAPHRAGM WITH A NOTE ON THE VENOUS DRAINAGE
container-title: Quarterly Journal of Experimental Physiology and Cognate Medical Sciences
items.abstract: <jats:p>In fifty‐three cats the arterial blood supply to the diaphragm was studied and some observations made on the venous drainage. The arteries arise from the 8th to 13th intercostal arteries, the internal mammary arteries and from branches of the abdominal aorta. Rarely there are direct branches from both the thoracic and the abdominal aorta. There are considerable variations in the pattern of supply. The veins drain into tributaries of the intercostal veins, the internal mammary veins and into the inferior vena cava.</jats:p>
